description:
For the past few years these vibrant and loud red-lored parrots have been visiting my neighborhood for a couple of weeks in the spring. They go from tree to tree ravaging the berries and leaving fallen leaves and berries all over the ground. They seem to visit a different tree everyday and spend between 15-30 minutes chowing down.

This flock had approximately 40-60 members. There was a couple that kept a close eye on me while the other ones fed. At times they were a bit playful. One thing that stood out to me was how well they blend into the tree because there were a mix of fall and spring colored leaves.

description:
Large flocks of non-native parrots populate Glendale and Burbank. For some reason they fly several miles north in the morning, then several miles back to the south at dusk, all while making a great deal of noise. One of the spots they favor is the Bette Davis Picnic Area near my home. When I heard them on this late afternoon, I followed with my camera. They took over several tall trees in the park and filled the air with their shrieks and cries. Not all were appreciative of their visit, and when they began investigating the nooks and crannies of a tall Sycamore, an outraged resident appeared and attempted to drive them off. 
It was an Acorn Woodpecker, protecting what was likely its nesting tree. Though the smaller bird seemed outmatched, it was aggressive... and persistent... and the parrots eventually decided to roost elsewhere.
An Acorn Woodpecker went on the offensive to drive off a noisy group of partying Red-crowned Parrots. Their posture tells the tale. Victory was assured.

These parrots are tough, made more so by the fact that they have been introduced to this area over many years by escape from captivity, and so have likely also interbred to a certain extent. A dozen or two were in my local park yesterday at dusk. I think these are likely Lilac-crowned due in part to the scalloping caused by dark edged feathers. The cere area around the nostril is darker than in others yesterday, but confusing since it is not dark or black as sometimes described. If possible, comment on the factors that informed your ID. And thanks.

This pair were together in the trees yesterday at dusk. They certainly make a cute couple and appear to be Re-crowned, which are the most common in this area, but have different amounts of red on the head. The cere area around the nostril is lighter in color than some of the others I saw. Please describe the significant details if you are able to make a positive ID.  Thanks...

description: Parrots are regular visitors to my neighborhood park, arriving in the evening and heading back north in the morning. This morning it was rather noisy and I noticed that a pair were together and a group of three or four seemed to be harassing them.Since there are several distinct species in this area, l became curious as to whether this disagreement had a "cultural" bias... like the Sharks and the Jets. At any rate, it was an excuse to take a few photos. And... it turned out that the original pair appear to be Lilac-crowned Parrots, while the others were Red-crowned. This is one of the Lilac-crowned with it distinctive dark nares and eye rings.

In a previous observation, I referred to a minor clash between two groups of parrots in the park this morning. The larger group was composed of what appeared to be the most common of our local visitors; Red-crowned Parrots, including this one. The most noticeable difference (to an amateur, like me) is the lighter color of the rings around the eyes and the nares.
